            <h1>What are the main types of color blindness, and how are they categorized based on the affected color-sensitive cells?</h1>
            <p class="f-pera">
              Color blindness, also known as color vision deficiency (CVD), can be categorized into two main types based on the specific color-sensitive cells that are affected:
            </p>
            <img class="types_blindness" src="/images/Color Chart.png" alt="types of color blindness">
            <p class="f-pera">
              <ol class="order">
                <li><strong>Red-Green Color Blindness:</strong> This is the most common type of color blindness, and it can further be divided into two subtypes: </li>
                <ul class="order">
                  <li><strong>Protanomaly:</strong> People with protanomaly have a reduced sensitivity to red light, making it difficult to distinguish between certain shades of red and green. </li>
                  <li><strong>Protanopia:</strong> People with protanopia lack the red-sensitive cones, making it impossible to perceive any red light. They may confuse red with green, blue, or gray. </li>
                </ul>
                <li><strong>Blue-Yellow Color Blindness:</strong> This type of color blindness is less common than red-green color blindness and can also be divided into two subtypes:</li>
                <ul class="order">
                    <li><strong>Deuteranomaly:</strong>People with deuteranomaly have a reduced sensitivity to green light, causing difficulties in distinguishing between certain shades of green and blue.</li>
                    <li><strong>Deuteranopia:</strong>People with deuteranopia lack the green-sensitive cones, leading to difficulties in differentiating between green and blue.</li>
                </ul>

              </ol>
              <p class="f-pera">It's crucial to remember that not everyone suffers colour blindness in the same manner, and that its intensity can range from moderate to severe. Colour blindness can also be inherited or developed later in life for a variety of reasons. The diagnosis of colour blindness and other visual abnormalities might be aided by routine eye exams.</p>

