          <h1>What is the Ishihara test, and what is the procedure for conducting this test to assess color vision deficiency?</h1>
          <p class="f-pera">A typical test to assess colour blindness, also known as colour vision deficit, is the Ishihara test. It was initially introduced in 1917 by Dr. Shinobu Ishihara, who gave it its name. The test consists of a succession of plates with dots of different colours that are set such that those with normal colour vision can identify or detect certain numbers or patterns among the dots, whereas people with colour vision deficits may find it challenging to do so.</p>
          <p class="f-pera">At first, the test-taker will initially be presented a plate; if he properly recognises it, the test will move on; if not, it will end and the test-taker has a major colour vision problem.</p>
          <p class="f-pera"> Following that, the test-taker will be presented with another set of 20 plates. If they correctly identify the numbers or patterns on more than 17 plates, it indicates they do not have color blindness. However, if they score lower than 13, it suggests they have color blindness. Subsequently, the test-taker will be shown 4 additional plates, and based on their responses to these plates, the specific type of color blindness can be determined.</p>
